According to the World Health Organization, 100 million litres of blood are missing worldwide to meet the needs of the world's population.
In addition, the French Blood Establishment informs us that 90% of French people know that blood donation can save lives.
And despite this figure, only 4% to carry out this gesture every year.
And this scenario is repeated in most industrialized countries.
Faced with this gap between human blood donations and the needs of the world population, we must find an alternative to this practice, in order to respond to this real public health problem.
And, as amazing as it may seem, I may have found one of the solutions.
And the solution, I found it on a beach in Brittany.
Already small, I was fascinated by the oceans, and I think that the emissions of Commander Cousteau were not foreign.
So I naturally decided to make it my profession, and I became a doctor in marine biology.
An environment caught my attention very early on, because this environment was colonized by very old organisms.
This environment is the foreshore, or a scientific name for an environment that you must appreciate since in fact, it is the beach.
And the beach in Brittany is covered twice a day by the tide.
And the sand of this beach is home to very old organisms that you have certainly seen, by the traces that these organisms leave on the sand, by laying your towel.
In fact, these traces testify to the presence of a marine organism called the arenaculture.
So the arenicole is the name of a marine worm very well known on the beaches in Brittany whose name in Breton is the Buzuc.
So I was interested in this seaworm to answer questions of respiratory ecophysiology.
So what does that mean?
Oh, it's simple, I was interested in the breathing of this seaworm.
I was trying to actually understand how this worm was breathing between high and low tide.
And in order to answer this question of basic research, (Laughter) I was interested in the blood of this animal.
Blood is an extremely interesting biological fluid.
It is the interface between the physiology of an organism and its environment.
In fact, blood is composed of different cells, but the molecule that carries oxygen, the oxygen essential to all living organisms, which is a little - if I took an example related to mechanics - oxygen, it's a bit the fuel you're going to put in your vehicle.
Fuelless is the dry breakdown.
And without oxygen, it's life-saving death.
In fact, blood contains a type of cell called red blood cells.
Red blood cells are a small vehicle that will transport the gas to the cells of your body.
And to be more precise, this molecule contains a protein called hemoglobin.
Hemoglobin is a molecule that is able to reversibly bind oxygen.
And what was not my surprise, to discover that the blood of this marine worm here had no red blood cells.
Oh, I have to be honest, when I started my discovery, I didn't know the extent of this work.
But [my discovery] went back to the ears of a learned club, which is called the Club du Globule Rouge.
(Laughter) So I was invited to Paris, in a Parisian hospital to present my research work in front of a bed of doctors, hematologists.
And at the end of my scientific conference, several of them went down to the bottom of the amphi and asked me the following questions: “But Sir, you have not found this molecule that has this structure, who has this function? »
"Well, yes! »
“But we’ve been looking for this molecule for over 40 years to make it a universal blood substitute! »
You and I have an ABO blood type, positive rhesus or negative Rhesus.
Only the negative O is of the universal donor type.
The absence of red blood cells in this animal gave this molecule a universal character.
And back in the laboratory, in order to test this hypothesis, I hastened to go to the beach to collect a few hundred areniculturals, simply to try to collect them the hemoglobin contained in their circulatory system, and after purification of this molecule by conventional laboratory techniques, I hastened to transfuse rodents.
And what was not my surprise, after exsanguination of these laboratory animals at more than 80%, I transfused this molecule to these animals, and nothing happened.
(Laughter) The organisms, these rodents, lived with marine worm hemoglobin.
An amazing discovery, and today a huge hope for medicine.
A nose to all these skeptics who asked me the question: "But what's the point of studying the breathing of a seaworm?
(Laughter) You really don't have other things to do in a CNRS lab? »
(Laughter) In order to accompany this research, I am forced to leave the CNRS to create a biotechnology company that will be responsible for developing these molecules towards medical applications.
And it only takes a few hundred grams of arenagoes to make a globular type pocket.
The applications of this molecule are numerous.
Why?
Well simply because oxygen is at the center of all biological and physiological processes, so, ultimately, life.
In the early years of the creation of this company, I spent them developing an industrial process of producing my seaworms.
Indeed, by being a biologist, it was out of the question for me to go and discard all the beaches in Brittany.
And today, these worms are produced in aquaculture, in a totally controlled and traced environment.
Several hundred tonnes of this animal are produced in aquaculture.
Apart from the worm, the raw material, the biomass, it was also necessary to find an industrial production system for the extraction of these molecules under pharmaceutical conditions.
And today, we actually have a whole process that allows to extract molecules from biomass.
From this industrial and marine worm production process, the applications are extremely numerous.
And I'll name three of them, but there are a lot of them.
First is blood transfusion.
You know, when you donate your blood, a pocket of blood can be kept 42 days, because the red blood cells are perishable.
In addition, it is necessary to maintain the cold chain at 4 °C.
I remind you that this molecule is not contained in a red blood cell.
And it is thus possible to obtain freeze-dried blood, that is to say powdered blood, which can be put back into solution thanks to pharmaceutical water.
So no more storage problems.
More conservation problem at 4 °C.
This product could be quickly available on emergency areas, on cataclysm areas, where you really need to transfuse patients.
This product is now in development thanks to a partnership with the U.S. military.
The second application is healing.
So not any type of wound.
Wounds that will be found in people who suffer from diabetes, called diabetic foot syndrome, people who suffer from pressure ulcers, the big burns, all these wounds have the characteristic of poorly healing.
Why?
Well simply because the blood circulation is hurting.
And unfortunately, the wounds that will be found in people with diabetes usually end badly since most of these people are amputated.
And this affects 20 million people around the world.
We were able to show that dressings impregnated by this molecule were capable of delivering oxygen to the feet, therefore in these wounds, and therefore, ultimately, to avoid amputation.
The third of these applications, which is now the most successful since a human trial will take place at the end of the year, is organ transplantation.
In France, 500 people die per year for lack of grafts on a waiting list of 19 000 patients.
Why?
Because in fact, the solutions that are used today in the clinic are composed only of water and salt but no oxygen carrier.
When an organ is removed from a donor, it is immediately disconnected from the bloodstream.
And we were able to show that by using this molecule, it was possible to significantly increase the retention time of a graft.
A heart today is four hours, between the collection at the donor's home and the time when we go to the recipient.
A kidney is 12 hours.
With this molecule, today, we were able to double the conservation time of these organs and multiply by four the retention time of a kidney.
So today, we are able to increase the pool of grafts available for transplantation.
The search is moving forward, but it is not moving as fast as we would like.
Why?
Because the drug cycle is long, very long, very, very long, and while waiting for the marketing of our product, which could save millions of lives around the world, I can only encourage you to go and donate your blood.
Be generous in saving lives.
And a little advice with friends, go fast, because tomorrow, it could be a gesture of another time.
Thank you.
