Today there is more of a tourist since the 2010 kidnappings.
There are migrants, hundreds and hundreds of migrants from West Africa.
The mayor entrusted me: to the season conducive to migration, the population of the city triples.
In 2 weeks when it will be less hot.
39° instead of 45.
For those who cross the Sahara in the back of the pickup trucks to Libya, that counts.
So you're going to tell me: not yet stories of migrants, we hear only that.
And if I told you that we don't actually talk about it anymore.
We're only talking about refugees.
The ones we show you on TV are Syrians, Iraqis.
They are fleeing a war.
We were told that they are doctors, lawyers, that at home they have a big house, a housekeeper.
They're a bit like us, they're white.
I cover Africa for Le Point magazine.
And the ones I've started watching since June, they're the ones we don't want at home.
They are poor, not very educated, they are black.
They will never have refugee status.
They will always be confined to the migrant on the move.
When the Syrians take a few weeks to reach Europe, they take several years.
Many people get stuck in Libya.
Some are murdered for no reason.
Many die on the way to the Sahara.
The desert is littered with corpses.
